ReCell Project¶

Background¶

  • ReCell is a startup aiming to tap the potential in the used and refurbished phone market that has grown considerably over the past decade.
  • ReCell believes that the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost the demand for cheaper used smartphones as these devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses.
  • However, since this is a relatively under-the-radar market, an attempt is being made to devise an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished smartphones.
  • A linear regression model is being built to predict the price of a used phone and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The dataset consists of the following variables:

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the phone runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the phone battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the phone in grams
  • release_year: Year when the phone model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished phone has been used
  • new_price: Price of a new phone of the same model in euros
  • used_price: Price of the used/refurbished phone in euros

Objectives¶

To explore the dataset and extract insights from it using Exploratory Data Analysis before building a model with it. More specifically, an attempt is being made to answer the following questions:

  • What does the distribution of used phone prices look like?
  • What percentage of the used phone market is dominated by Android devices?
  • The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a phone. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  • A large battery often increases a phone's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones offering large batteries (more than 4500 mAh)?
  • Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  • Budget phones nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of budget phones offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  • Which attributes are highly correlated with the used phone price?

Furthermore, preprocessing the data to make it ready for analysis and modeling.

Finally, building a Linear Regression Model to guage the significance of predictors on the price of a used smartphone.

Q1 What does the distribution of used phone prices look like?¶

In [16]:
# Here is a function that plots a combined histogram and boxplot for any input numerical variable.
# Defining a function will enable running the code faster.


def dist_box(df):
    fg, ax = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.75, 0.25)},
        figsize=(10, 6),
    )  # Creating Subplot grid with 2 rows, with shared x-axis
    fg.suptitle(
        "Descriptive Statistics for " + df.name,
        fontsize=18,
        ha="center",
        fontweight="heavy",
    )  # Giving Title to the graph
    sns.distplot(df, bins=30, kde=False, color="seagreen", ax=ax[0])
    # Creating Histogram
    ax[0].axvline(
        df.mean(), color="coral", linestyle="--", linewidth=3, label="Mean"
    )  # Adding Mean to the histogram
    ax[0].axvline(
        df.median(), color="darkgreen", linestyle="-.", linewidth=3, label="Median"
    )  # Adding Median to the histogram
    ax[0].axvline(
        df.mode()[0], color="blue", linestyle=":", linewidth=3, label="Mode"
    )  # Adding Mode to the histogram
    ax[0].legend()  # Plotting the legend
    sns.boxplot(
        df, orient="h", showmeans=True, color="pink", ax=ax[1]
    )  # Creating box plot, with a marker to indicate the mean value of the column
In [17]:
dist_box(phone["used_price"])

Observations¶

  • As can be seen from the above distribution of histogram and box plot, the distribution for used_price is heavily right skewed.
  • The outliers to the right indicate that many used phones have a very high price.
  • The used_price ranges from around 2 euros to 1900 euros, with the average price being around 110 euros
  • The median used_price is around 75 euros, indicating 50 percent of used phones are priced less than 75 euros and 50 percent priced more than 75 euros.
  • The third quartile (75 percent) is 126, signifying 25 percent of used phones are priced more than 126 euros, while the first quartile (25 percent) is 45, meaning 25 percent of used phones are priced less than 45 euros.
  • The right whisker of the box plot extends all the way to around 1900 euros, indicating the maximum price for used phone(s).
  • The mode at 60 euros indicates the most frequently occuring price for used phones.
  • Since the above distribution is highly skewed, used_price might behave better on the log scale. This would form a part of data preprocessing.

Observations¶

  • On the lower end, Celkon along with some other brands, has phones with the lowest ram (0.03-0.25 GB)
  • Further on, looking at the relationship between ram and price of these used phones might provide interesting insights.

Q6 What is the distribution of budget phones offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?¶

Since the price points of the phones have not been defined, column binning is being carried out to categorize phones into three segments:¶

  • Low-range/Budget phones
  • Mid-range phones
  • High-range phones
  • The new price would form the base for budget phone classification since the customer will buy the phones at new price.
  • For binning by distance, the cut() function in pandas will be employed and the interval range for each group will be specified.
  • Since, by using binning by distance and calculating the interval range using the maximum and minimum value of the column and using the linspace() function is yielding unsatisfactory intervals, we will resort to binning manually by using the 1st and 3rd quartile as bin breaks.

Outlier Treatment¶

  • Quantile-based Flooring and Capping is being applied for treating the above outliers for continuous variables.
  • Since, the variables main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp, int_memory and ram have discrete values, we won't do outlier treatment for these.
In [60]:
# Defining a function for treating outliers


def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: dataframe
    col: name of the column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """
    treat outlier in all numerical variables
    col_list: list of numerical variables
    df: data frame
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df
In [61]:
# Treating the outliers

col_list = ["screen_size", "battery", "weight", "used_price"]
phone = treat_outliers_all(phone, col_list)

Model performance evaluation¶

  • Let's check the performance of the model using different metrics - RMSE, MAE, and 𝑅2.
  • A function is being defined to calculate MAPE and adjusted 𝑅2.
In [84]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    # Function which will print out all the above metrics in one go
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

The following Linear Regression assumptions will be checked:

  • No Multicollinearity

  • Linearity of variables

  • Independence of error terms

  • Normality of error terms

  • No Heteroscedasticity

a) TEST FOR MULTICOLLINEARITY¶

  • Multicollinearity occurs when predictor variables in a regression model are correlated.

  • This correlation is a problem because predictor variables should be independent.

  • Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) is being used to test for multicollinearity.

    • If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation among the 𝑘 th predictor and the remaining predictor variables, and hence, the variance of 𝛽𝑘 is not inflated at all.

  • General Rule of thumb:

    • If VIF is between 1 and 5, then there is low multicollinearity.
    • If VIF is between 5 and 10, we say there is moderate multicollinearity.
    • If VIF is exceeding 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.
In [88]:
pd.set_option("display.float_format", lambda x: "%.5f" % x)
In [89]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Define a function to check VIF
def checking_vif(predictors):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # Calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]
    return vif

TEST FOR LINEARITY AND INDEPENDENCE¶

  • Linearity describes a straight-line relationship between two variables, predictor variables must have a linear relation with the dependent variable.
  • Also, the independence of the error terms (or residuals) is important.
  • A plot of fitted values vs residuals would help gauge if there is presence of a pattern in the data and if it is showing signs of non-linearity and residuals are not independent.
  • If present, this will be fixed by trying to transform the variables and making the relationships linear.

Removing non-linearity and dependence of residuals¶

To fix this assumption:

  • We will try to transform the study variables, first target/dependent variable, used_price using log transformation.
    • Since the distribution of used_price is highly skewed, log transformation is being employed so that the variable behaves better and gets closer to a near normal distribution.
  • Transformation is always tried in dependent variables first because the residuals that cause heteroscedasticity is because of dependent variable and not the independent features.
  • If required after this, we will try to transform the independent variables as well, using log transformation.
  • We will then look at the scatter plot of the distribution of residuals (errors) vs fitted values (predicted values) again and then run the model.

TEST FOR NORMALITY¶

  • Error terms, or residuals, should be normally distributed. Non-normality suggests that there are a few unusual data points that must be studied closely to make a better model.
  • The shape of the histogram of residuals can give an initial idea about the normality.
  • Further, normality will be checked via a Q-Q plot of residuals. If the residuals follow a normal distribution, they will make a straight line plot, otherwise not.
  • The Shapiro-Wilk test statistic will also be calculated.
    • Null hypothesis: Residuals are normally distributed
    • Alternate hypothesis: Residuals are not normally distributed
In [102]:

plt.title("Normality of residuals")
plt.show()
  • The histogram of residuals does have a bell shape.
  • Let's check the Q-Q plot.

# Plotting a Q-Q plot for checking normality of residuals

import pylab

plt.show()
  • The residuals more or less follow a straight line except for the upper tail.
  • Let's check the results of the Shapiro-Wilk test.
In [104]:
# Calculating the Shapiro-Wilk test statistic

stats.shapiro(phone_pred["Residuals"])
Out[104]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9815012812614441, pvalue=1.617643835767684e-17)

Findings¶

  • Since p-value < 0.05, the residuals are not normal as per the Shapiro-Wilk test.
  • However, as an approximation, we can accept this distribution as close to being normal.
  • So, the assumption is satisfied.

TEST FOR HOMOSCEDASTICITY¶

  • The presence of non-constant variance in the error terms results in heteroscedasticity. Generally, non-constant variance arises in presence of outliers.
  • The residual vs fitted values plot created earlier will be looked into again to check for homoscedasticity. In the case of heteroscedasticity, the residuals can form an arrow shape or any other non-symmetrical shape.
  • The goldfeldquandt test will also be used. If we get a p-value > 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. Otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.
    • Null hypothesis: Residuals are homoscedastic
    • Alternate hypothesis: Residuals have heteroscedasticity
In [105]:
# Employing the goldfeldquandt test to check for heteroscedasticity

import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(phone_pred["Residuals"], x_train1)
lzip(name, test)
Out[105]:
[('F statistic', 1.0059235900636918), ('p-value', 0.4587197613914659)]

Findings¶

Since p-value > 0.05, we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. So, this assumption is satisfied.

Conclusions - Interpretation of above Regression Results¶

  • Looking at the Adjusted. R-squared, we get to know the fit of the model.
    • The value for Adj. R-squared is 0.867, which is high and indicates a good fit. It means 86.7 % of the variation in the dependent/target variable, used_price, is explained by the independent/predictor variables.
  • The value of the const coefficient/Y-intercept is 54.3521
  • Looking at the coefficients of predictors, screen_size, main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp, ram, weight, os_iOS, 4g_1, price_bin_Mid-range phones and price_bin_High-range phones have positive coefficients. This means as these increase, used_price also increases.
  • int_memory, battery, release_year, days_used, os_Others, os_Windows and 5g_1 have negative coefficients. This implies a negative relationship between these variables and used_price.
  • Looking at the p-values for the predictors, their significance can be checked at 0.05 (5%) significance level. A p-value of less than 0.05 is considered to be statistically significant.
    • int_memory, battery, os_Windows and 5g_1 are the only variables that are not significant. Consequently, they do not make much contribution to the prediction of used_price.
    • main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp, ram, weight, release_year, days_used, os_Others, os_iOS, 4g_1, price_bin_Mid-range phones and price_bin_High-range phones have come out to be very significant and influence the used_price greatly.
    • screen_size with a p-value of 0.024 is also a significant variable in predicting price of a used phone.

Key Insights based on EDA¶


  • Android devices dominate the used phone market to the extent of over 90 percent.

  • OnePlus, Apple and Google, in that order, have the most expensive phones.

  • 82 percent used phones that form a part of the sample have a ram of 4GB.

  • Although iOS devices at 1.6 percent form the least share of the used phone market, the most expensive phones run on iOS, and fetch twice the price as compared to the second most expensive - Android phones.

  • In fact, there are no low-range/budget phone that run on iOS, which implies that every iOS device sold fetches more money for the seller as compared to selling phones operating on other operating systems.

  • Three bins, namely, Low-range/Budget phones, Mid-range phones and High-range phones were created based on the new_price. These correspond to Low-Cost Brands, Mid-Range Brands and High-End Brands respectively.

  • The gradual slope of the graph for low-range/budget used phones indicates that there is less variation in the price for this category as compared to mid-range and high-range phones.

  • The least expensive high-range and mid-range phones run on Windows and 5G is not available in low-range/budget phones.

  • The used phone price has a relatively strong positive correlation with selfie_camera_mp, ram and screen_size, signifying that a higher selfie_camera_mp, a higher ram and a bigger screen_size translate into a higher used_price.

  • It was observed that very few low-range/budget phones have good quality selfie cameras. This should be kept in mind while targeting the desired customers.

  • The used phone price has a negative correlation with days_used, which is logical as greater the number of days a phone has been already used for, lower should be its price.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • ReCell, being a startup, should focus on building a wide customer base by way of Penetration Pricing. This would entail initially making available a wide variety of low-cost phones to the customers, with a view to building visibility and reception.
  • ReCell could engage in customer segmentation based on preference for low-cost phones, mid-range phones and high-priced phones by its customers.
  • As price variation is the least for low-cost phones, ReCell should devise a dynamic pricing strategy for mid-range phones and high-priced phones.
  • As Android devices dominate the used phone market, ReCell should maintain sufficient inventory based on a market demand-supply analysis.
  • As iOS devices are the most expensive and cater to a niche segment of customers, ReCell should be mindful of holding a lot of high-value inventory at the outset, before estimating the spending capacity of their prospective customers.
  • If however the current demand is for high-cost and feature-rich phones, ReCell could leverage such demand by selling iOS devices as an average iOS phone fetches more than double the price of any other phone.
  • Bigger screens, higher ram and better quality camera (significantly influence the used_price) are features that customers look for in a phone. ReCell should keep this is in mind while planning its inventory management.
  • As newer phones fetch a higher price, ReCell should aim at assigning cut-off dates for clearing off old inventory.
  • To create an exclusive experience to its customers and contain conpetition from online marketplaces, along with a physical storefront ReCell should build an online presence as well.
